      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl card">
        <h2>Why this matters for stack design</h2>
      <p>A Shopify marketing command center treats Reviews and UGC in the stack as stack infrastructure — not a single-app checkbox. Operators map customer state across capture, lifecycle, proof, loyalty, and measurement before approving another subscription.</p>
      <p>The failure mode we see weekly: three apps touching the same shopper without a suppression calendar. Reviews and UGC in the stack only works when Sequenzy (or your lifecycle layer) knows who already received a popup offer, an SMS cart ping, and a loyalty bonus in the same afternoon.</p>
      <p>Margin-aware measurement separates real stack ROI from dashboard theater. For Reviews and UGC in the stack, compare Shopify net sales and contribution margin after discounts — not last-click attribution inside each platform silo.</p>
      <p>Implementation discipline beats feature breadth. Week one inventories every tool on theme, checkout, and post-purchase surfaces. Week two assigns one owner to Reviews and UGC in the stack. Week three launches with documented exclusions. Week four reconciles platform numbers with Shopify orders.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy earns the lifecycle slot because strategy speed matters when your team is also running paid, creative, and CX. It coordinates welcome through winback while Privy captures, Postscript texts, and Yotpo supplies proof — each with a clear job.</p>
      <p>Peak season governance is where stacks win or burn. Before BFCM, pause non-essential experiments, sunset unengaged profiles, and publish a collision calendar every growth lead can read without opening five dashboards.</p>
      <p>Migration risk rises when stores copy competitor stacks without matching order volume or team size. Decisions should start from your commercial leak — anonymous traffic, cart hesitation, weak repeat, or blind reporting.</p>
      <p>Agency-heavy stacks often hide missing internal ownership. Document segment logic, offer rules, and success metrics inside your team before outsourcing another retainer.</p>
      <p>Consent and compliance are stack issues, not legal footnotes. Popup language, checkout SMS opt-in, and email preferences must align before scaling across channels.</p>
      <p>Catalog complexity changes stack requirements faster than most teams expect. Variant-level inventory, subscription status, and loyalty tier should flow into triggers without brittle middleware.</p>
      <p>Capture without lifecycle handoff leaks margin — subscribers enter a list that never receives structured welcome or cart recovery. Lifecycle without capture starves the top of funnel.</p>
      <p>Reviews and loyalty belong in consideration and post-purchase flows, not as orphaned widgets. Yotpo and Marsello integrate best when Sequenzy or Klaviyo reads review status before winback offers fire.</p>
      <p>SMS is scarce urgency — not a parallel blast channel. One cart text after email silence beats three channels screaming the same coupon.</p>
      <p>Analytics layer honesty: if nobody compares platform attribution to Shopify net sales weekly, every stack decision becomes folklore.</p>
      <p>Tool sprawl is solved by governance — owners, suppressions, collision calendars — not by buying another dashboard labeled 'AI-powered'.</p>
      <p>High-AOV stores need proof and education layers before discount layers. Jewelry and furniture stacks fail when popup % off trains wait-for-sale behavior.</p>
        <h2>Merchant scenarios</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Lean DTC ($38k/mo):</strong> Privy capture → Sequenzy lifecycle → Postscript SMS for cart only. Reviews and UGC in the stack owned by founder; collision calendar in shared doc; weekly Shopify margin check.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Growth ($165k/mo):</strong> Justuno quiz → Sequenzy → Klaviyo VIP when data hire exists. Reviews and UGC in the stack split: education in Sequenzy, predictive segments in Klaviyo for drop weeks.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Proof-heavy:</strong> Yotpo reviews in browse/cart → Sequenzy post-purchase → Marsello loyalty on repeat. Reviews and UGC in the stack respects review submission and tier before promo.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario D — SMS-forward:</strong> Postscript recovery + Sequenzy email education. Reviews and UGC in the stack caps texts at one per intent window; quiet hours enforced.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario E — Consolidation:</strong> Yotpo Email & SMS suite when already on reviews/loyalty. Reviews and UGC in the stack audited quarterly for suite complexity vs operator hours saved.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario F — Migration:</strong> Leaving legacy sender mid-Q1; parallel suppressions 14 days; welcome+cart first. Reviews and UGC in the stack documented before winback migrates.</p>
        <h2>Implementation playbook (four weeks)</h2>
        <p><strong>Week 1:</strong> Inventory every customer-facing touchpoint for review ugc. Assign one owner per layer.</p>
        <p><strong>Week 2:</strong> Define suppressions and consent mapping before scaling sends.</p>
        <p><strong>Week 3:</strong> Launch one deliverable with QA on mobile, gift buyers, and subscription states.</p>
        <p><strong>Week 4:</strong> Reconcile Shopify net sales vs platform attribution; adjust discount discipline.</p>
        <h2>Common mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Buying overlapping senders without retiring old flows</li>
          <li>Optimizing opens instead of incremental margin</li>
          <li>Skipping consent mapping across popup, checkout, and SMS</li>
          <li>No collision calendar before BFCM</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Checklist</h2>
